Here's a simple C++ function that converts some basic Markdown formatting to HTML. This function only handles headers (#), bold (**), and italic (*) formatting. For a more comprehensive solution, you may want to use a Markdown parsing library like `cpp-markdown` or `discount`.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdownText) {
    std::string htmlText = markdownText;

    // Replace headers (#) with <h1> tags
    std::regex headerRegex("^# (.+)$", std::regex::multiline);
    htmlText = std::regex_replace(htmlText, headerRegex, "<h1>$1</h1>");

    // Replace bold (**text**) with <strong> tags
    std::regex boldRegex("\\*\\*(.*?)\\*\\*");
    htmlText = std::regex_replace(htmlText, boldRegex, "<strong>$1</strong>");

    // Replace italic (*text*) with <em> tags
    std::regex italicRegex("\\*(.*?)\\*");
    htmlText = std::regex_replace(htmlText, italicRegex, "<em>$1</em>");

    return htmlText;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Header\n\n**Bold text**\n\n*Italic text*";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);
    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This code defines a `markdownToHtml` function that takes a `const std::string&` as input and returns a `std::string`. It uses the `std::regex_replace` function from the `<regex>` header to replace Markdown formatting with corresponding HTML tags.

